Pizzaman

**Origin:** [London, England](/London)
**Genres:** [Breakbeat](/Breakbeat), [house](/House_music), [tech house](/Tech_house)
**Years active:** 1993–1997
**Labels:** [Cowboy](/Cowboy_Records)
**Past members:** John Reid, [Norman Cook](/Norman_Cook)

Pizzaman was, for a fleeting period, a British electronic music duo, a collaboration that briefly illuminated the mid-1990s dance music scene before one member, predictably, eclipsed the other. The creative force behind this venture comprised [John Robinson Reid](/John_Robinson_Reid) (born 6 September 1963, deceased 16 June 2025) and [Norman Cook](/Norman_Cook) (born 31 July 1963). What began as a venture into the burgeoning soundscapes of [breakbeat](/Breakbeat), [house](/House_music), and [tech house](/Tech_house) ultimately served as a prelude, at least for one of its architects, to a far grander narrative in electronic music history. Their output, though brief, managed to capture a certain effervescent energy characteristic of the era, even if its legacy is often overshadowed by subsequent, more monumental achievements.

### Biography

The duo’s sole album, aptly titled "*Pizzamania*", made its debut in 1995. This release emerged during a particularly fertile period for electronic music, where the lines between underground club culture and mainstream pop appeal were becoming increasingly blurred. The album, a collection of tracks designed to ignite dancefloors and infiltrate airwaves, proved to be more than just a fleeting effort, at least initially.

From "*Pizzamania*", three singles were extracted, each accompanied by a music video crafted under the direction of [Michael Dominic](/Michael_Dominic), a visual artist known for his distinctive style. These promotional efforts paid off, with all three tracks managing to secure a spot within the coveted top forty on the [UK Singles Chart](/UK_Singles_Chart). This was no small feat in a competitive landscape, indicating a public appetite for Pizzaman's brand of electronic energy.

The initial front-runner in terms of chart performance was "[Happiness](/Happiness_(Pizzaman_song))", which peaked at a respectable #19. However, the capricious nature of the music industry often allows for second acts, and "[Trippin' on Sunshine](/Trippin%27_on_Sunshine)" experienced a minor resurgence. Originally released in 1994, it was re-released the following year, a strategic move that saw it climb slightly higher, securing the #18 position. One might observe that such marginal improvements often mean more to record labels than to the cosmic indifference of the universe, but for the duo, it represented a tangible, if slight, increase in commercial validation.

Despite this promising, albeit modest, chart success, the momentum proved difficult to sustain. The only subsequent material to emerge from Pizzaman was the 1996 single, "Hello Honky Tonks (Rock Your Body)". This standalone track, a non-album single, hinted at a potential new direction or perhaps a struggle to coalesce new material into a cohesive album project. Ultimately, it signaled the diminishing output before the project's eventual conclusion.

One of Pizzaman's most notable and, arguably, audacious tracks, "[Sex on the Streets](/Sex_on_the_Streets)", featured a rather unexpected sample. The song incorporated a segment from a 1974 sermon delivered by the American evangelist [Jack van Impe](/Jack_van_Impe). The juxtaposition of a fire-and-brimstone sermon with a track titled "[Sex on the Streets](/Sex_on_the_Streets)" speaks volumes about the irreverent spirit of 90s dance music, where boundaries were meant to be pushed, if not entirely obliterated. It demonstrated a willingness to subvert expectations and inject a dose of provocative irony into their sound, making the track memorable for more than just its beat.

The Pizzaman project ultimately disbanded in 1997. Following this cessation, [Norman Cook](/Norman_Cook) embarked on a solo career that would redefine his public persona and achieve a level of global renown that far surpassed his earlier endeavors. He found significantly greater success under the moniker [Fatboy Slim](/Fatboy_Slim), a name that would become synonymous with big beat music and stadium-filling DJ sets. It's almost as if some collaborations are merely stepping stones, designed to launch one participant into the stratosphere while the other watches from a slightly lower orbit.

Tragically, [John Robinson Reid](/John_Robinson_Reid) passed away from cancer on 16 June 2025, at the age of 61. His contributions to Pizzaman, and undoubtedly to other musical projects, represent a part of the vibrant tapestry of British electronic music, even if much of the collective memory tends to focus on the subsequent trajectory of his more famous collaborator. His passing marks the definitive end of an era for the duo.

### Discography

The discography of Pizzaman, while concise, offers a snapshot of their brief but impactful presence in the 1990s dance music landscape. It primarily consists of one studio album and a handful of singles, each attempting to capture a piece of the contemporary musical zeitgeist.

